{{Infobox comics creator | image = | imagesize = 150 | caption = | birth_name = | birth_place = [[Connecticut]] | death_place = | nationality = [[United States|American]] | cartoonist = y | write = | art = y | pencil = | ink = | edit = | publish = | letter = | color = | alias = | signature = <!-- very optional --> | notable works = | awards = Meriden Hall of Fame, 2003 | website = | subcat = American | birth_date={{Birth date and age|1934|09|07}} }} '''Warren Sattler''' (born September 7, 1934)<ref name="CBG">{{cite web|last=Miller|first= John Jackson| url=http://cbgxtra.com/knowledge-base/for-your-reference/comics-industry-birthdays |title=Comics Industry Birthdays| work= [[Comics Buyer's Guide]]| date=June 10, 2005| accessdate= December 12, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5trAbNQWw | archivedate=October 29, 2010}}</ref> is an [[United States|American]] [[artist]] and [[cartoonist]], who contributed work to many popular publications from the early 1960s through the 1990s.
==Biography== A lifelong [[Connecticut]] resident,<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070927212433/www.chs.org/comics/creators.htm |archivedate= September 27, 2007|title= Connecticut Talent|publisher= [[Connecticut Historical Society]]|url=http://www.chs.org/comics/creators.htm}}</ref> Warren Sattler started cartooning at an early age and was first published in a newspaper at age 15.{{citation needed|date=January 2011}} He got his education at the Wilcox Technical School in [[Meriden, Connecticut]].{{citation needed|date=January 2011}} He later taught at the [[Famous Artists School]] from 1957 to 1962.{{citation needed|date=January 2011}} In the 1960s, he assisted on the [[comic strip]]s ''[[Barnaby (comic strip)|Barnaby]]'' and ''[[The Jackson Twins]]''. Sattler also drew comics that appeared in ''[[Help! (magazine)|Help]]'' magazine under the direction of [[Harvey Kurtzman]]. His own strip, ''Grubby'', ran from 1964 to 1997.{{citation needed|date=January 2011}}
In the 1970s, Sattler produced art for [[comic book]]s, in particular [[Charlton Comics]]. Some titles he worked on include ''[[Billy the Kid (Charlton Comics)|Billy the Kid]]'', ''[[Fightin' Army]]'', ''[[Fightin' Marines]]'', ''[[Ghost Manor (comics)|Ghost Manor]]'', ''[[Ghostly Haunts]]'', and ''Yang''. Additionally, he worked as an illustrator for ''[[Cracked (magazine)|Cracked]]'' magazine, ''[[National Lampoon (magazine)|National Lampoon]]'', and ''[[Playboy]]''. Sattler created a second syndicated comic strip in 1980: ''Swamp Brats'', a [[Sunday strip|Sunday-only strip]]. He [[ghostwriter|ghosted]] on such newspaper strips as ''[[Bringing Up Father]]'', ''Comics for Kids'' and ''[[Gil Thorp]]'' during the 1980s and 1990s.
==Awards== In 2003, he was inducted into the [[Meriden, Connecticut|Meriden]] Hall of Fame.<ref>{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060503092725/http://www.record-journal.com/articles/2003/11/03/news/news02.txt |date=May 3, 2006 |title=Meriden Hall of Fame }}</ref>
